With our headquarters at 123 Tech Street, Accra, and satellite offices in Kumasi, Lagos, Nairobi, and Johannesburg, we are strategically positioned to serve the diverse needs of the African market. 2   Clients and Partners Savannah Intelligence collaborates with a wide array of clients and partners, reflecting our deep ties to Ghana and the broader African ecosystem: •   Jumia Ghana : Enhancing online retail with AI-driven customer personalization and supply chain optimization. •   MTN Ghana :   Strengthening mobile money services with secure, AI-powered fraud detection. •   Ghana Post : Improving last-mile delivery through AI logistics solutions. •   Ecobank Ghana : Partnering to develop fintech innovations for cross-border pay- ments. •   Ghana Ministry of Communications and Digitalization :   Supporting na- tional efforts to advance digital literacy and inclusion. Globally, we partner with tech giants such as Google AI, Microsoft Azure, and IBM Watson, integrating their cutting-edge tools with our localized expertise to deliver world- class solutions tailored for Africa.

 Savannah Intelligence 1   Company Overview Savannah Intelligence, established in 2020, is a trailblazing technology company head- quartered in the vibrant city of Accra, Ghana. Rooted in the heart of West Africa, we harness the power of artificial intelligence (AI) to address the unique challenges and opportunities within the African e-commerce and fintech sectors.

Linguistic Diversity :   Ghanas 80+ languages and diverse con- sumer preferences complicate personalization. •   Data Utilization Gap : Many Ghanaian businesses lack the tools to harness data for strategic decision-making. Our AI solutions tackle these issues head-on, offering secure, efficient, and culturally attuned tools to drive digital success. 4   Savannah AI Suite The Savannah AI Suite is our flagship platform, designed with Ghanaian and African businesses in mind: •   Savannah Commerce : Features recommendation engines, dynamic pricing, and inventory forecasting, tailored for markets like Ghanas bustling Makola Market traders. •   Savannah Pay : Offers fraud detection, AI credit scoring for Ghanas unbanked, and payment optimization for mobile money platforms like MTNs MoMo. •   Savannah Logistics :   Provides route optimization and demand prediction, ad- dressing Ghanas rural-urban delivery divide. •   Savannah Insights : Delivers analytics dashboards in English and local languages like Twi, empowering SMEs with actionable insights.

Our mission is to em- power Ghanaian and African businesses with innovative AI solutions that enhance growth, streamline operations, and foster financial inclusion. Our vision is to lead Africas digital transformation, creating a future where technology drives economic prosperity across the continent. Founded by Dr. Kwame Mensah, a Ghanaian fintech visionary with over 15 years of experience, and Dr. Aisha Osei, an esteemed AI researcher from the University of Ghana, Savannah Intelligence reflects a deep commitment to leveraging local expertise for global impact. Our team of over 50 professionals includes Ghanaian data scientists, machine learning engineers, and blockchain specialists, all dedicated to bridging the technological divide in Africa. Since our launch, weve marked significant milestones:   securing $5 million in seed funding from African and international investors, launching the Savannah AI Suite in 2021, and establishing partnerships with key players across Ghana and beyond.

 Savannah Intelligence •   Limited Banking Access : With only 43% of Ghanaians accessing formal banking (2022 African Development Bank), fintech is vital for financial inclusion. •   Cross-Border Payment Barriers : High fees and delays impede trade, especially for SMEs in Ghanas export-driven economy. •   Logistics Constraints : Rural roads and urban congestion challenge e-commerce delivery, with Ghanas infrastructure still evolving. •   Transaction Security Concerns :   Fraud and cyber threats erode trust, with Ghana reporting a 20% rise in online scams in 2023 (Ghana Cybercrime Unit). •   Cultural and Linguistic Diversity :   Ghanas 80+ languages and diverse con- sumer preferences complicate personalization.
